 0030: """
 0031: This module contains classes and functions for working with chemical reactions.
 0032: 
 0033: From the `IUPAC Compendium of Chemical Terminology
 0034: <http://dx.doi.org/10.1351/goldbook>`_, a chemical reaction is "a process that
 0035: results in the interconversion of chemical species".
 0036: 
 0037: In RMG Py, a chemical reaction is represented in memory as a :class:`Reaction`
 0038: object. This module also provides the :class:`ReactionModel` class for
 0039: representing a set of chemical reactions and the species involved.

This function will try to use the best method that it\n        can based on the input data available:\n        \n        * If detailed information has been provided for the transition state (i.e.\n          the molecular degrees of freedom), then RRKM theory will be used.\n        \n        * If the above is not possible but high-pressure limit kinetics\n          :math:`k_\\infty(T)` have been provided, then the inverse Laplace \n          transform method will be used.\n    \n        The density of states for the product `prodDensStates` and the temperature\n        of interest `T` in K can also be provided. For isomerization and association\n        reactions `prodDensStates` is required; for dissociation reactions it is\n        optional.  0870:         """
 0871:         Calculate the microcanonical rate coefficient :math:`k(E)` for the reaction
 0872:         `reaction` at the energies `Elist` in J/mol. `reacDensStates` and
 0873:         `prodDensStates` are the densities of states of the reactant and product
 0874:         configurations for this reaction. If the reaction is irreversible, only the
 0875:         reactant density of states is required; if the reaction is reversible, then
 0876:         both are required. This function will try to use the best method that it
 0877:         can based on the input data available:
 0878: 
 0879:         * If detailed information has been provided for the transition state (i.e.
 0880:           the molecular degrees of freedom), then RRKM theory will be used.
 0881: 
 0882:         * If the above is not possible but high-pressure limit kinetics
 0883:           :math:`k_\\infty(T)` have been provided, then the inverse Laplace
 0884:           transform method will be used.
 0885: 
 0886:         The density of states for the product `prodDensStates` and the temperature
 0887:         of interest `T` in K can also be provided. For isomerization and association
 0888:         reactions `prodDensStates` is required; for dissociation reactions it is
 0889:         optional. The temperature is used if provided in the detailed balance
 0890:         expression to determine the reverse kinetics, and in certain cases in the
 0891:         inverse Laplace transform method.
 0892:         """
